  "nursesNote": "Assertiveness training helps a patient express needs and feelings directly and respectfully while honoring both their own and others' rights, which is the healthiest communication style. It contrasts with passive communication (suppressing one's needs and avoiding conflict), aggressive communication (hostile, blaming, 'you' statements that violate others' rights), and passive-aggressive communication (indirect resistance, sarcasm, or the silent treatment). The nurse teaches 'I' statements (for example, 'I feel ___ when ___, and I need ___'), calm tone, eye contact, confident posture, and how to set boundaries and say no respectfully. The nurse uses role-play and practice to build the skill. Assertive communication lowers conflict and stress and improves relationships and self-esteem.",
  "providerOrders": [
    "Teach the difference between passive, aggressive, and assertive styles",
    "Model and teach 'I' statements",
    "Encourage calm tone, eye contact, and confident posture",
    "Practice setting boundaries and saying no respectfully",
    "Use role-play to build the skill"
  ],
